summary:
Here is a concise summary of the Security Council document:

The Security Council, recalling its previous resolutions and statements on the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), reaffirms the country's sovereignty, territorial integrity, and political independence. The Council expresses deep concern at continued hostilities, particularly renewed fighting between Ugandan and Rwandan forces in Kisangani, and demands that these forces cease hostilities and withdraw from the city. The Council:

1. Calls on all parties to cease hostilities and fulfil their obligations under the Ceasefire Agreement and the Kampala disengagement plan;
2. Condemns the fighting between Ugandan and Rwandan forces in Kisangani and demands that they desist from further fighting;
3. Demands that Ugandan and Rwandan forces, as well as Congolese armed opposition and other armed groups, immediately and completely withdraw from Kisangani, and calls on all parties to respect the demilitarization of the city and its environs.
The Security Council:

Demands Uganda and Rwanda withdraw all forces from the Democratic Republic of Congo's territory without delay, in line with the Ceasefire Agreement and the 8 April 2000 Kampala disengagement plan (para 4(a));

Requires reciprocal withdrawal by other parties in accordance with the same timetable (para 4(b));

Calls for an end to all foreign military presence and activity in the Democratic Republic of Congo (para 4(c));

Demands all parties abstain from offensive action during disengagement and withdrawal (para 5);

Requests the Secretary-General to review arrangements for MONUC deployment to monitor ceasefire, disengagement, and withdrawal (para 6);

Calls on parties to cooperate with MONUC (para 7);

Demands parties cooperate with MONUC deployment, including lifting restrictions on movement and ensuring security (para 8);

Calls on Congolese parties to engage in National Dialogue (para 9);

Demands parties cease assistance to armed groups (para 10);

Urges parties to continue dialogue on disarmament, demobilization, resettlement, and reintegration (para 11);

Demands compliance with Ceasefire Agreement provisions on border security normalization (para 12);

Condemns massacres and atrocities, urging international investigation (para 13);

Suggests Governments of Uganda and Rwanda make reparations for damage inflicted on civilian population (para 14);

Calls on parties to protect human rights and respect humanitarian law (para 15);
